-1. Differential Privacy as a principled baseline
What it is: Add DP-SGD (Abadi et al. 2016) to your training loop via the opacus library. DP provides a mathematically proven privacy guarantee (ε, δ) — something CDML cannot claim.
Why it matters for your thesis: Right now CDML's privacy is demonstrated empirically but has no formal bound. DP gives you a formal competitor. The comparison becomes: CDML achieves similar empirical privacy to DP-SGD with ε≈3 but without the accuracy cost. That is a publishable claim. You can plot the (ε, accuracy, IIA AUC) three-way trade-off.
pythonfrom opacus import PrivacyEngine
privacy_engine = PrivacyEngine()
model, optimizer, loader = privacy_engine.make_private_with_epsilon(
    module=model, optimizer=optimizer, data_loader=loader,
    epochs=EPOCHS, target_epsilon=3.0, target_delta=1e-5, max_grad_norm=1.0)
Novel angle: Apply DP to the continual learning setting — does the privacy budget compound across tasks? Nobody has studied DP-SGD + sequential task training on gait data specifically.

-2. Federated learning setting
What it is: Instead of one model trained on all subjects, simulate a federated setup where each "client" holds one task's subjects. The server aggregates with FedAvg.
Why it's different from everything you've done: Your entire pipeline assumes centralised training. Federated learning is the realistic deployment scenario for a gait authentication system — hospitals or buildings with sensors would never send raw IMU data to a central server.
The attack surface changes completely: In federated learning the attacker is a malicious client who can inspect gradient updates, not model outputs. Implement a gradient inversion attack (Zhu et al. 2019) against your federated CDML and show whether the CDML sequence in the aggregated model still protects against it.
This could be Phase 13 and would be genuinely novel — federated CL with CDML has not been studied.

3. Completely different architecture: Transformer-based gait encoder
What it is: Replace the 4-layer CNN with a small Transformer (4 heads, 2 layers) operating on the 6-channel IMU sequence as a sequence of timesteps.
Why it matters: Transformers have a fundamentally different privacy profile. The attention mechanism creates explicit pairwise dependencies between timesteps, which may leak more (or less) identity information than convolutional features. Nobody knows for gait IMU data specifically. Then apply CDML to this Transformer's embedding, run your full attack battery, and compare. The question: does the richer feature space of a Transformer make it more vulnerable to IIA (more identity-discriminative features) or less (better generalisation)?

4. Data-level analysis: what makes a subject vulnerable?
What it is: This is the most under-explored dimension in your work. Instead of treating all 118 subjects equally, analyse which subjects are more vulnerable to MIA and why.
Concrete experiments:

Compute per-subject IIA AUC (you already have m_scores per subject in your IIA results)
Correlate vulnerability with: number of training windows, intra-subject gait variance, the subject's position in the task sequence (Task 1 vs Task 4)
Does CDML protect high-variance subjects (atypical gaits) and low-variance subjects (very consistent gaits) equally?

Why this is original: Every MIA paper reports aggregate AUC. Nobody looks at the distribution of vulnerability across subjects. If Task 1 subjects (trained earliest, most forgotten) are systematically less vulnerable than Task 4 subjects (trained most recently), that is a finding about the interaction between catastrophic forgetting and privacy.


